{"type":"text","timestamp":1775848177491,"sessionID":"ses_2873360e8ffe2cGitvBv9LQRIl","part":{"id":"prt_d78ccbc630012uChX7BA2zp2On","messageID":"msg_d78ccaf7e001662npWvA6LeplW","sessionID":"ses_2873360e8ffe2cGitvBv9LQRIl","type":"text","text":"I'll create a `delta-spec.md` file with GIVEN/WHEN/THEN scenarios for the AR-009 Router HTTP reverse proxy feature based on the provided specification.","time":{"start":1775848177488,"end":1775848177488}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775848234041,"sessionID":"ses_2873360e8ffe2cGitvBv9LQRIl","part":{"id":"prt_d78ccbf52001dvK9VnsclX0Z0v","messageID":"msg_d78ccaf7e001662npWvA6LeplW","sessionID":"ses_2873360e8ffe2cGitvBv9LQRIl","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_97fb119aabbe4db68be9855c","state":{"status":"error","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/delta-spec.md","content":"# Delta Specification: AR-009 — Router HTTP Reverse Proxy Core\n\n**Module:** `pkg/router`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M  \n**Type:** New Feature\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nThis specification defines the HTTP reverse proxy functionality for the AgentCube router module. The router will proxy HTTP requests from external clients to internal agent runtime services using Kubernetes client-go for service discovery.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### R-1: Router Initialization\n\n**Given** a valid Kubernetes cluster configuration  \n**When** the router is initialized with a `rest.Config`  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Create a clientset using `clientset.NewForConfig(config)`\n- Initialize the shared informer factory\n- Register event handlers for AgentRuntime resources\n- Return an error if the clientset creation fails\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Successful router initialization with valid config\n  Given a valid Kubernetes rest.Config pointing to a running cluster\n  When NewRouter(config) is called\n  Then the router SHALL be initialized successfully\n  And the clientset SHALL be created\n  And the informer factory SHALL be started\n  And no error SHALL be returned\n\nScenario: Router initialization fails with invalid config\n  Given an invalid rest.Config (e.g., unreachable API server)\n  When NewRouter(config) is called\n  Then the router SHALL fail to initialize\n  And an appropriate error SHALL be returned\n  And no resources SHALL be allocated\n\nScenario: Router initialization with custom HTTP client\n  Given a rest.Config and a custom *http.Client with TLS settings\n  When NewRouterWithClient(config, httpClient) is called\n  Then the router SHALL use the provided HTTP client\n  And the clientset SHALL be created with the custom client\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-2: HTTP Request Routing\n\n**Given** a running router with registered AgentRuntime services  \n**When** an HTTP request is received at the proxy endpoint  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Extract the target service identifier from the request path/headers\n- Look up the corresponding AgentRuntime resource using the typed client\n- Forward the request to the target service's endpoint\n- Preserve the original request method, headers, and body\n- Return the proxied response to the client\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Route request to existing AgentRuntime service\n  Given an AgentRuntime \"agent-a\" exists in namespace \"default\"\n  And the agent service is running at 10.0.0.1:8080\n  When an HTTP GET request is received at \"/default/agent-a/api/status\"\n  Then the router SHALL look up \"agent-a\" using AgentRuntimeInterface.Get()\n  And the request SHALL be forwarded to http://10.0.0.1:8080/api/status\n  And the response status code SHALL be proxied back to the client\n  And response headers SHALL be preserved\n\nScenario: Route request with custom headers\n  Given an AgentRuntime service is running\n  When an HTTP request with custom headers (Authorization, Content-Type) is received\n  Then the router SHALL forward all headers to the target service\n  And the Authorization header SHALL be preserved\n  And the Content-Type header SHALL be preserved\n\nScenario: Route POST request with body\n  Given an AgentRuntime service is running\n  When an HTTP POST request with JSON body is received\n  Then the router SHALL forward the request body unchanged\n  And the Content-Length header SHALL be updated appropriately\n  And the response SHALL be returned to the client\n\nScenario: Route request to non-existent service\n  Given no AgentRuntime named \"non-existent\" exists\n  When a request is received for \"/default/non-existent/api\"\n  Then the router SHALL return HTTP 404 Not Found\n  And an error message SHALL indicate the service was not found\n\nScenario: Route request to inactive service\n  Given an AgentRuntime exists but has no ready endpoints\n  When a request is received for that service\n  Then the router SHALL return HTTP 503 Service Unavailable\n  And the response SHALL indicate no healthy endpoints\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-3: Service Discovery via Informers\n\n**Given** the router is running in a Kubernetes cluster  \n**When** AgentRuntime resources are created, updated, or deleted  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Use the SharedInformerFactory to watch for changes\n- Update its internal service registry on Add events\n- Update endpoint information on Update events\n- Remove services from the registry on Delete events\n- Handle informer cache sync on startup\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: New AgentRuntime is added\n  Given the router is running with informer watches active\n  When a new AgentRuntime \"agent-b\" is created in namespace \"default\"\n  Then the informer OnAdd handler SHALL be triggered\n  And the service SHALL be added to the router's registry\n  And subsequent requests SHALL be routable to \"agent-b\"\n\nScenario: AgentRuntime is updated\n  Given an AgentRuntime \"agent-a\" is registered in the router\n  When the AgentRuntime's endpoint IP changes from 10.0.0.1 to 10.0.0.2\n  Then the informer OnUpdate handler SHALL be triggered\n  And the router's registry SHALL be updated with the new endpoint\n  And subsequent requests SHALL be forwarded to 10.0.0.2\n\nScenario: AgentRuntime is deleted\n  Given an AgentRuntime \"agent-a\" is registered in the router\n  When the AgentRuntime is deleted from the cluster\n  Then the informer OnDelete handler SHALL be triggered\n  And the service SHALL be removed from the router's registry\n  And subsequent requests SHALL return 404\n\nScenario: Router startup with cache sync\n  Given multiple AgentRuntime resources exist in the cluster\n  When the router starts and initializes informers\n  Then WaitForCacheSync SHALL be called\n  And all existing AgentRuntimes SHALL be loaded into the registry\n  And the router SHALL be ready to serve requests after sync\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-4: Namespace-Based Routing\n\n**Given** the router supports multi-tenancy via Kubernetes namespaces  \n**When** a request includes a namespace in the path  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Extract the namespace from the request path (e.g., `/{namespace}/{service}/...`)\n- Use namespace-scoped informer listers for service lookup\n- Only route to services within the specified namespace\n- Return 404 if namespace does not exist or has no matching service\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Route to service in specified namespace\n  Given AgentRuntime \"svc-a\" exists in namespace \"ns-1\"\n  And AgentRuntime \"svc-a\" also exists in namespace \"ns-2\" with different endpoint\n  When a request is received at \"/ns-1/svc-a/api\"\n  Then the router SHALL use AgentRuntimeLister.AgentRuntimes(\"ns-1\")\n  And the request SHALL be forwarded to the \"ns-1\" endpoint only\n\nScenario: Request to non-existent namespace\n  Given namespace \"non-existent\" does not exist\n  When a request is received at \"/non-existent/svc-a/api\"\n  Then the router SHALL return HTTP 404 Not Found\n  And the error SHALL indicate namespace not found\n\nScenario: List services in namespace\n  Given multiple AgentRuntimes exist in namespace \"default\"\n  When a request is received at \"/default/__list__\"\n  Then the router SHALL return a list of all services in \"default\"\n  And the response SHALL include service names and statuses\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-5: Health Check Endpoint\n\n**Given** the router is running  \n**When** a health check request is received  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Expose a `/healthz` endpoint\n- Return HTTP 200 if the router is healthy\n- Check informer cache sync status\n- Verify clientset connectivity\n- Return detailed status in response body\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Health check when router is healthy\n  Given the router is running with all informers synced\n  When an HTTP GET request is received at \"/healthz\"\n  Then the router SHALL return HTTP 200 OK\n  And the response body SHALL indicate \"healthy\"\n  And the informer sync status SHALL be included\n\nScenario: Health check when informers not synced\n  Given the router is starting but informers have not synced\n  When an HTTP GET request is received at \"/healthz\"\n  Then the router SHALL return HTTP 503 Service Unavailable\n  And the response SHALL indicate cache not synced\n\nScenario: Health check when clientset disconnected\n  Given the router lost connection to Kubernetes API server\n  When an HTTP GET request is received at \"/healthz\"\n  Then the router SHALL return HTTP 503 Service Unavailable\n  And the response SHALL indicate API server connection issue\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-6: Connection Pooling and Timeouts\n\n**Given** the router proxies HTTP requests to backend services  \n**When** establishing connections to target services  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Use a configurable connection pool\n- Set request timeout (default: 30s)\n- Set idle connection timeout (default: 90s)\n- Reuse connections for repeated requests to same backend\n- Handle connection errors gracefully\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Request completes within timeout\n  Given a backend service responds within 5 seconds\n  And the request timeout is set to 30 seconds\n  When a request is proxied to the backend\n  Then the request SHALL complete successfully\n  And the response SHALL be returned to the client\n\nScenario: Request times out\n  Given a backend service takes 60 seconds to respond\n  And the request timeout is set to 30 seconds\n  When a request is proxied to the backend\n  Then the router SHALL return HTTP 504 Gateway Timeout\n  And the connection SHALL be closed\n\nScenario: Connection pool exhaustion\n  Given the connection pool is at capacity\n  When a new request arrives\n  Then the router SHALL wait for an available connection\n  And if none available within timeout, return HTTP 503\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-7: Error Handling and Logging\n\n**Given** the router handles proxied requests  \n**When** errors occur during routing  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Log all routing decisions and errors with structured logging\n- Include request ID, namespace, service name, and method in logs\n- Return appropriate HTTP status codes for different error types\n- Not expose internal error details to clients\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Log successful routing\n  Given a request is successfully routed to a backend\n  When the request completes\n  Then a log entry SHALL be written with level INFO\n  And the log SHALL include method, path, namespace, service, status code, and duration\n\nScenario: Log routing failure\n  Given a request fails to route (service not found)\n  When the routing fails\n  Then a log entry SHALL be written with level ERROR\n  And the log SHALL include error reason and request details\n  And the client SHALL receive a generic error message\n\nScenario: Log backend error\n  Given a backend returns HTTP 500\n  When the response is proxied back\n  Then a log entry SHALL be written with level WARN\n  And the log SHALL include backend status code\n  And the response SHALL be returned to the client unchanged\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-8: Graceful Shutdown\n\n**Given** the router is running and handling requests  \n**When** a shutdown signal is received  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Stop accepting new requests\n- Wait for in-flight requests to complete (max 30s)\n- Shutdown the informer factory\n- Close all pooled connections\n- Release all resources\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Graceful shutdown with no active requests\n  Given the router is running with no active requests\n  When a SIGTERM signal is received\n  Then the router SHALL stop the HTTP server\n  And the informer factory SHALL be shut down\n  And all resources SHALL be released\n  And the process SHALL exit with code 0\n\nScenario: Graceful shutdown with active requests\n  Given the router is handling 5 in-flight requests\n  When a SIGTERM signal is received\n  Then the router SHALL wait for requests to complete (up to 30s)\n  And new requests SHALL be rejected with HTTP 503\n  And after all requests complete, shutdown SHALL proceed\n  And the process SHALL exit with code 0\n\nScenario: Forceful shutdown timeout\n  Given the router has long-running requests (>30s)\n  When a SIGTERM signal is received\n  Then the router SHALL wait up to 30s for requests to complete\n  And after 30s, the router SHALL force shutdown\n  And the process SHALL exit with code 0\n```\n\n---\n\n## Dependencies\n\n| Dependency | Source | Usage |\n|------------|--------|-------|\n| `k8s.io/client-go` | `client-go/` | Kubernetes API client |\n| `k8s.io/apimachinery` | Generated types | Resource types and metav1 |\n| `net/http/httputil` | Go stdlib | Reverse proxy implementation |\n| `go.uber.org/zap` | External | Structured logging |\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n1. **Unit Tests**: Mock clientset and informers for router logic\n2. **Integration Tests**: Use fake clientset (`clientset/versioned/fake`) with test server\n3. **E2E Tests**: Deploy to test cluster with real AgentRuntime resources\n\n---\n\n## Security Considerations\n\n- RBAC: Router service account requires `get`, `list`, `watch` permissions on AgentRuntimes\n- Authentication: External authentication layer required (not in scope)\n- Authorization: Namespace isolation enforced by routing logic\n- Rate limiting: To be implemented in future iteration\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. Should the router support WebSocket connections? (Deferred to AR-010)\n2. Should request/response transformation be supported? (Out of scope)\n3. Should circuit breaker pattern be implemented? (Deferred to AR-011)\n"},"error":"You must read file /home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/delta-spec.md before overwriting it. Use the Read tool first","time":{"start":1775848234030,"end":1775848234038}}}}
